                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.52/164.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">Consul <persName type="from">Letcher</persName> to the <gloss
                            type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>.</hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">American Consulate</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Chihauhua</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-12">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 12, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Department’s January 23 and February 7. General Chao, acting governor, informed
                    me yesterday very frankly that no investigation of the killing of the two
                    Spanish brothers on December 13 [12] has been made and further that they had
                    been executed by superior military order, meaning by order of Villa, under the
                    law known as the Juarez Decree of 1862 which has reference to foreigners taking
                    up arms in domestic conflicts. As far as I can learn the Spaniards who were
                    executed were not implicated in political or military measures adverse to the
                    present authorities.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Letcher</hi>
                    </signed>.</closer>
            </div>
        </body>
